<p>I have a large <code>NumPy.array</code> <code>field_array</code> and a smaller array <code>match_array</code>, both consisting of <code>int</code> values. Using the following example, how can I check if any match_array-shaped segment of <code>field_array</code> contains values that exactly correspond to the ones in <code>match_array</code>?</p>  <pre><code>import numpy raw_field = ( 24,  25,  26,  27,  28,  29,  30,  31,  23, \               33,  34,  35,  36,  37,  38,  39,  40,  32, \              -39, -38, -37, -36, -35, -34, -33, -32, -40, \              -30, -29, -28, -27, -26, -25, -24, -23, -31, \              -21, -20, -19, -18, -17, -16, -15, -14, -22, \              -12, -11, -10,  -9,  -8,  -7,  -6,  -5, -13, \               -3,  -2,  -1,   0,   1,   2,   3,   4,  -4, \                6,   7,   8,   4,   5,   6,   7,  13,   5, \               15,  16,  17,   8,   9,  10,  11,  22,  14) field_array = numpy.array(raw_field, int).reshape(9,9) match_array = numpy.arange(12).reshape(3,4) </code></pre>  <p>These examples ought to return <code>True</code> since the pattern described by <code>match_array</code> aligns over <code>[6:9,3:7]</code>.</p>